The "Power Law" as described for Bitcoin does not apply to Dogecoin because Dogecoin lacks the fundamental "scarcity engine" and physical growth characteristics that the Bitcoin Power Law depends on.
‚ÄãWhile Dogecoin has a large following, its mathematical structure is the opposite of the one shown in your slides. Here is why:
‚Äã1. No Maximum Cap (Infinite vs. Finite)
‚ÄãYou mentioned a "maximum cap of 168 billion," but Dogecoin actually has no maximum supply.  
‚ÄãFixed Inflation: Every year, 5 billion new Dogecoins are created‚Äîforever.  
‚ÄãThe Math: Because the supply grows every year, the "value" of each individual coin is constantly being diluted. A Power Law requires a stable, fixed base (like the 21 million BTC) to act as a "mathematical floor".  
‚Äã2. Physical System vs. Social Hype
‚ÄãThe Bitcoin Power Law treats Bitcoin like a growing city (infrastructure and innovation growing with the population).  
‚ÄãBitcoin's "City": It has thousands of full-time developers and massive energy-intensive security (mining) that grows predictably over time.
‚ÄãDogecoin's "Meme": Dogecoin has very few active developers and its value is driven primarily by social media virality and "hype" rather than long-term infrastructure growth. Hype cycles are exponential and unstable, not long-term Power Laws.  
‚Äã3. "Feature, Not a Bug"
‚ÄãInterestingly, some supporters (like Elon Musk) argue that Dogecoin's inflation is a good thing.  
‚ÄãThey believe it makes Dogecoin a better transactional currency (spending money) because people are less likely to hoard it.  
‚ÄãHowever, the Power Law is a model for Store of Value (savings). Because Dogecoin is designed to be "spent," it doesn't build up the same mathematical "monetary energy" over decades that Bitcoin does.
The Verdict: While Dogecoin can have massive price spikes, it doesn't follow the "Log-Log" straight line of Bitcoin because its supply isn't fixed and its network growth isn't tied to the same physical laws of energy and time.
